#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: actors-supervision
description: Actor Phase 2 — trapExit / link / monitor / demonitor
---

# Actor Supervision

Phase 2 actor primitives: `link`, `monitor`, `demonitor`, `trapExit`.

## trapExit + link: Exit signal arrives as a message

A process with `trapExit(true)` receives an `Exit` message when a linked
actor crashes instead of dying itself.

```scalascript
runActors {
  val sup = spawn { () =>
    trapExit(true)
    val worker = spawn { () =>
      println("worker starting")
      val me = self()
      exit(me, "crash")
    }
    link(worker)
    receive {
      case Exit(from, reason) => println("supervisor caught: " + reason)
    }
  }
}
```

## link without trapExit: crash propagates silently

When `trapExit` is not set, a linked crash kills the linked actor without
producing any output.  Unrelated actors continue normally.

```scalascript
runActors {
  val b = spawn { () =>
    val me = self()
    exit(me, "kaboom")
  }
  val a = spawn { () =>
    link(b)
    receive { case _ => println("a unreachable") }
  }
  println("root done")
}
```

## monitor: Down message on crash

`monitor` delivers a `Down` message when the watched actor exits abnormally.

```scalascript
runActors {
  val watcher = spawn { () =>
    val worker = spawn { () =>
      val me = self()
      exit(me, "oops")
    }
    val ref = monitor(worker)
    receive {
      case Down(r, from, reason) => println("down: " + reason)
    }
  }
}
```

## demonitor: cancel before Down is delivered

After `demonitor`, no `Down` is delivered even if the watched actor exits.

```scalascript
runActors {
  val watcher = spawn { () =>
    val worker = spawn { () =>
      println("working")
      val me = self()
      exit(me, "done")
    }
    val ref = monitor(worker)
    demonitor(ref)
    println("no down received")
  }
}
```
